 //!
 //! There is no CRLF special-casing: `'\r'` is an ordinary whitespace
 //! character and lands in the length of its line.
+//!
+//! Accumulators are *mergeable*: shard a file on UTF-8 boundaries, feed each
+//! shard into its own [`TextStats`], and [`TextStats::merge`] the partial
+//! states in order. The state is a monoid — the pieces that touch a shard
+//! edge (the open first/last line, the partial first/last token) are kept
+//! unresolved until `merge` or `summary` glues them, so any fold shape gives
+//! the same answer as one accumulator that saw the whole stream.
